reference "fig:PRES-CLEF2010"

\end_inset

 shows the PRES obtained for all the QE methods, while selecting the optimal
 number of terms used for the expansion (number of terms that maximizes
 the performance for each method).
 From these results, we make the following observations:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The best section to use for querying is the description section (see Figure
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:qDescription-PRES-CLEF-IP2010"

\end_inset

).
 We attribute this to the fact that the description section has more content
 along with relevant terms that define the invention since a detailed summary
 of the invention is described therein.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The best source for query expansion is the claims section.
 We attribute this to the fact that, the claims contain not only relevant,
 but also, specific terminology, since the scope of the invention is described
 therein.
 However, when querying using the claims, other sources of query expansion
 provided better performance.
 This may be because claims are very similar between them and contained
 specific terms; consequently, the queries lack of diversity and general
 terms or synonyms that are used to describe similar inventions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The description section is not either a good source for expansion, since
 its content is too broad; therefore, it contains many irrelevant terms
 that hurt the performance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Query expansion is not useful for very long queries (i.e.
 description), indicating that in advanced stages of the patent application
 process, QE is not relevant.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
When dealing with more mid-long queries such as abstract or claims, MMRQE
 is more effective than Rocchio, which suggest that diverse term selection
 is not crucial for short queries.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Using the IPC code definitions (as suggested by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
